# **1. File & Folder Structure**

*The single most important structural decision you will make: organize by feature, not by type.*

## **Feature-Based Folder Structure**

Every file related to a feature lives in one folder. When you work on Users, you open one folder — not six.

| **❌  BAD /src  /models    user.model.js    order.model.js  /controllers    user.controller.js    order.controller.js  /services    user.service.js    order.service.js** | **✅  GOOD /src  /users    user.model.js    user.service.js    user.controller.js    user.exceptions.js    user.test.js  /orders    order.model.js    order.service.js    order.controller.js** |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

## **File Size Limits — Hard Rules**

| **File Type**       | **Hard Limit** | **Action if Exceeded**             |
| ------------------- | -------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| Any source file     | \> 400 lines   | Split into sub-modules             |
| Any function/method | \> 40 lines    | Extract to named helper            |
| Any class           | \> 300 lines   | Apply SRP, split by responsibility |
| Main/entry file     | \> 80 lines    | Move logic to dedicated modules    |

## **File Naming Convention**

- Use kebab-case for filenames: user-auth.service.js, not UserAuthService.js or userauthservice.js
- Suffix files by their role: .service, .controller, .model, .repository, .exceptions, .utils, .test
- Never mix two roles in one file. No user-and-order.service.js
- Index files (index.js / __init__.py) expose the public API only — never contain logic

## **Shared / Utility Layer**

Create a /shared or /common folder for code used across 2+ features. If something is used by only one feature, it belongs inside that feature's folder — not in shared.

/src/shared/  date.utils.js  http.utils.js  validators.js  base.exception.js

# **2. The Main File Contract**

*The main file is a table of contents. It bootstraps, registers, and delegates. It never implements.*

## **What Belongs in Main**

- App bootstrap (create_app(), init_server())
- Configuration loading
- Dependency wiring (connect DB, register middleware)
- Route/handler registration via function calls
- Starting the server/process

## **What Never Belongs in Main**

- Business logic of any kind
- Database queries
- Validation logic
- try/catch blocks for business errors
- More than one level of nesting

| **❌  BAD # Bad main.pyfrom flask import Flask, requestapp = Flask(__name__)@app.route('/users', methods=['POST'])def create_user():    data = request.get_json()    if not data.get('email'):        return {'error': 'missing email'}, 400    db.execute("INSERT INTO users ...")    send_welcome_email(data['email'])    return {'ok': True}, 201** | **✅  GOOD # Good main.pyfrom app import create_appfrom config import load_configfrom database import init_dbfrom routes import register_routesdef main():    config = load_config()    db = init_db(config)    app = create_app(config)    register_routes(app, db)    app.run(port=config.PORT)if __name__ == "__main__":    main()** |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

**RULE:** If you are writing an if statement in main, you are implementing, not bootstrapping. Move it out.

## **Bootstrap Order**

Always initialize in this order to prevent dependency failures at startup:

- 1. Load config and environment variables
- 2. Initialize logger
- 3. Connect to external services (DB, cache, queues)
- 4. Create app instance
- 5. Register middleware
- 6. Register routes
- 7. Start server / begin processing

# **3. Clean Code & Naming**

*Code is read 10x more than it is written. Optimize for the reader, not the writer.*

## **Naming Rules — No Exceptions**

| **Entity**     | **Convention**               | **Example**                     |
| -------------- | ---------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Variable       | Descriptive noun/noun phrase | activeUserCount, not n or cnt   |
| Function       | Verb + object                | fetchUserById(), not getData()  |
| Boolean        | is/has/can prefix            | isAuthenticated, hasPermission  |
| Class          | PascalCase noun              | OrderProcessor, UserRepository  |
| Constants      | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE         | MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS              |
| Private method | _prefix or private keyword   | _buildQuery(), #validateInput() |

## **Function Design Rules**

- A function does ONE thing. If you write 'and' describing it — split it.
- Functions that return boolean should be named as a question: isExpired(), canRetry().
- A function that takes more than 3 parameters needs a parameter object.
- Avoid flag arguments (true/false params). They signal the function does two things.

| **❌  BAD // takes 6 args, flag param, unclear namefunction process(u, t, true, 0, null, cb) {  // no idea what this does}** | **✅  GOOD // self-documenting, object paramfunction sendPasswordResetEmail({ user, template, expiresInMinutes }) {  // immediately clear}** |
| --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

## **Comment Policy**

Comments explain WHY, never WHAT. If the code needs a comment to explain what it does, rewrite the code until it doesn't.

| **❌  BAD // loop through usersfor (const u of users) {  // check if active  if (u.status === 1) { ... }}** | **✅  GOOD // Throttle is per-user, not per-IP, to prevent// account sharing abuse (see ticket #4421)for (const user of activeUsers) {  applyRateLimit(user);}** |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

**RULE:** Delete commented-out code immediately. Git history is your backup, not your source file.

# **4. Zero Code Duplication (DRY)**

*If you copy a block of code, you now own two bugs instead of one. The second will be found at 2am in production.*

## **The Three-Strike Rule**

The first time you write logic, write it. The second time you need the same logic, copy it with a note. The third time — stop and extract it into a shared function. No exceptions.

## **Where Shared Code Lives**

- Logic shared by 2+ features → /shared/utils/
- Logic shared by 2+ classes in a feature → private helper in that feature's service
- Logic shared across services (error formatting, HTTP responses) → /shared/base/ or a base class
- Cross-cutting concerns (auth, logging, rate-limiting) → middleware layer, never copied inline

## **Inheritance vs. Composition**

Use inheritance for genuine 'is-a' relationships. Use composition for code reuse. Copying methods across classes because you can't decide is neither — it is duplication with extra steps.

| **❌  BAD class UserService:    def _format_date(self, d):        return d.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')class OrderService:    def _format_date(self, d):  # duplicated!        return d.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')** | **✅  GOOD # shared/date_utils.pydef format_date(d):    return d.strftime('%Y-%m-%d')# user.service.pyfrom shared.date_utils import format_date#** [**order.service.py**](http://order.service.py)**  from shared.date_utils import format_date** |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |

## **Template / Base Classes**

For repeated structural patterns (REST controllers, repositories, validators), create a base class with the shared structure and override only what differs. Every concrete class should be thin.

class BaseRepository:    def find_by_id(self, id): ...    def find_all(self): ...    def save(self, entity): ...    def delete(self, id): ...class UserRepository(BaseRepository):    def find_by_email(self, email): ...  # only the unique method

# **5. Exception Handling — Every try Has a catch**

*A silent failure is worse than a crash. At least a crash tells you something broke. Swallowing an exception tells you nothing and corrupts your system state invisibly.*

## **The Absolute Rules**

- Every try block has a catch/except. No exceptions.
- Every catch block either handles the error, logs it, or re-raises it. It never does nothing.
- Never catch the base Exception class unless you immediately log full context and re-raise.
- Never use bare except: in Python. Ever.
- Always raise domain-specific exceptions, not strings or generic errors.

| **❌  BAD try:    result = fetch_data()except:    pass  # silent death# also bad:try:    process_payment()except Exception:    print("error")  # no context, no re-raise** | **✅  GOOD try:    result = fetch_data()except NetworkTimeoutError as e:    logger.error("Fetch timed out", extra={"url": url, "error": str(e)})    raise ServiceUnavailableError("Upstream timeout") from eexcept ValueError as e:    logger.warning("Invalid response format", extra={"error": str(e)})    raise DataValidationError("Bad upstream data") from e** |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

## **Custom Exception Hierarchy**

Every domain owns its exceptions. Catching generic exceptions across domain boundaries means you cannot distinguish a DB error from a validation error from a network error.

\# shared/base_exceptions.pyclass AppBaseException(Exception):    def __init__(self, message, error_code=None):        super().__init__(message)        self.error_code = error_code# users/user_exceptions.pyclass UserNotFoundException(AppBaseException): passclass UserAlreadyExistsException(AppBaseException): passclass InvalidUserDataException(AppBaseException): pass# orders/order_exceptions.pyclass OrderNotFoundException(AppBaseException): passclass PaymentDeclinedException(AppBaseException): pass

## **Exception Layer Responsibility**

| **Layer**            | **Raises**                       | **Handles**                              |
| -------------------- | -------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Repository / DAO     | DatabaseException                | Raw DB errors only                       |
| Service              | Domain exceptions (UserNotFound) | Maps DB → domain exceptions              |
| Controller / Handler | HTTP exceptions (404, 400)       | Maps domain → HTTP responses             |
| Global error handler | Nothing                          | Catches all unhandled, logs, returns 500 |

**RULE:** Never let a database exception bubble up to the HTTP response layer. Each layer translates exceptions to its own vocabulary.

# **6. Logging Standards**

*Logs are your system's memory. If an incident happens at 3am and the logs don't tell you exactly what broke, why, and which user/request was involved — your logging is wrong.*

## **Never Use print() / console.log() in Production Code**

print() has no level, no structured fields, no timestamps, and cannot be filtered. Replace every print() with a proper logger call before the PR is merged.

## **Log Levels — Exact Usage**

| **Level** | **Use When**                         | **Example**                             |
| --------- | ------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------- |
| DEBUG     | Detailed dev-only trace info         | SQL query with params, loop iterations  |
| INFO      | Normal system events worth recording | User logged in, order created           |
| WARN      | Something unexpected but recovered   | Retry succeeded after 2 failures        |
| ERROR     | Operation failed, needs attention    | Payment declined, DB write failed       |
| CRITICAL  | System integrity threatened          | DB connection pool exhausted, disk full |

## **Structured Logging — Required Fields**

Every log entry must carry structured context, not just a string. This allows filtering, alerting, and dashboards.

| **❌  BAD # unstructured - unsearchablelogger.error("Payment failed for user 123")** | **✅  GOOD # structured - filterable, alertablelogger.error(    "Payment processing failed",    extra={        "user_id":** [**user.id**](http://user.id)**,        "order_id":** [**order.id**](http://order.id)**,        "amount_cents": payment.amount,        "gateway": payment.gateway,        "error_code": e.code,        "request_id":** [**request.id**](http://request.id)**  # trace across services    })** |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |

## **What to Always Log**

- Service startup and shutdown with config summary (no secrets)
- Every external API call: endpoint, duration, status code
- Every DB query that takes > 500ms (slow query log)
- Every authentication event: login, logout, failed attempt, token refresh
- Every state-changing operation: create, update, delete — with who did it
- Every caught exception, with full stack trace at ERROR level

## **What to Never Log**

- Passwords, tokens, API keys, credit card numbers — even partially
- Full request bodies that may contain PII unless explicitly required and encrypted
- Secrets from environment variables

**RULE:** Run a log scrubber in CI that fails the build if patterns like 'password', 'token', 'secret' appear in log statements.

# **7. OOP & Logic Separation**

*The question is never 'does this work?' It's 'which layer is responsible for this?'. Logic in the wrong layer is the cause of 80% of architectural rot.*

## **Single Responsibility — One Job Per Class**

A class is responsible for exactly one thing. The test: can you describe this class's job in one sentence without using 'and'?

| **❌  BAD class UserManager:    def create_user(self): ...    def send_welcome_email(self): ...    def generate_pdf_report(self): ...    def log_audit_trail(self): ...    # This class has 4 jobs** | **✅  GOOD class UserService:    def create_user(self): ...  # one jobclass EmailService:    def send_welcome_email(self): ...class ReportService:    def generate_user_report(self): ...class AuditLogger:    def log(self, event): ...** |
| --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |

## **Strict Layer Contracts**

| **Layer**    | **Knows About**               | **Must NOT Know About**          |
| ------------ | ----------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Controller   | HTTP req/res, DTOs            | Database queries, business rules |
| Service      | Domain models, business rules | HTTP, database drivers, SQL      |
| Repository   | Database, SQL, ORM            | Business logic, HTTP             |
| Domain Model | Its own data and validation   | Everything external              |

## **Dependency Inversion — Depend on Interfaces**

Services should depend on abstractions (interfaces/abstract classes), not concrete implementations. This enables testing with mocks and swapping implementations.

\# Bad: Service knows about the concrete classclass OrderService:    def __init__(self):        self.repo = PostgresOrderRepository()  # hard-coded# Good: Service depends on abstractionclass OrderService:    def __init__(self, order_repo: OrderRepositoryInterface):        self.order_repo = order_repo  # injected, swappable

## **Encapsulation Rules**

- All class fields are private by default. Expose only what consumers absolutely need.
- Never allow external code to mutate internal state directly. Use methods.
- If you find yourself accessing obj.inner.value.thing — you have a law of Demeter violation. Add a method to obj.

# **8. Testing Standards**

*Tests are not optional. Untested code in a large codebase is a landmine waiting for someone to step on it during a Friday refactor.*

## **Test Pyramid — Ratios**

| **Type**          | **Volume** | **Speed**    | **What It Tests**                  |
| ----------------- | ---------- | ------------ | ---------------------------------- |
| Unit tests        | ~70%       | < 1ms each   | Single function/class in isolation |
| Integration tests | ~20%       | < 500ms each | 2+ components wired together       |
| End-to-end tests  | ~10%       | Seconds      | Full user flow through system      |

## **Unit Test Rules**

- Unit tests NEVER hit the database, filesystem, or network. Use mocks/fakes.
- One test file per source file. user.service.test.js lives next to user.service.js.
- Test behavior, not implementation. Test what the function returns, not how it does it internally.
- Each test has exactly one assertion of business behavior (multiple expect() calls for one concept is fine).
- Test names are sentences: 'should throw UserNotFoundException when user does not exist'

## **What Must Always Be Tested**

- Happy path: valid input produces correct output
- Null/empty/zero inputs — every boundary case
- Every custom exception being raised under the right conditions
- Every conditional branch (if/else/switch arms)
- Any function that touches money, permissions, or data deletion

## **Coverage**

Target 70-80% line coverage as a minimum enforced in CI. But coverage is a floor, not a goal. A function that is 'covered' by a test that never asserts anything is worse than no test — it creates false confidence.

**RULE:** A test with no assertions, or that only asserts 'it did not throw', is not a test. It is a placeholder.

# **9. Version Control & CI/CD**

## **Commit Message Convention — Enforced**

Use Conventional Commits. This is enforced by a commit-msg git hook, not a suggestion.

feat(auth): add OAuth2 login with Googlefix(orders): prevent duplicate charge on retrychore(deps): bump express from 4.17 to 4.18refactor(users): extract email validation to shared utilstest(payments): add unit tests for refund edge casesdocs(api): update POST /users endpoint documentation

- feat: new functionality visible to users
- fix: bug fix visible to users
- chore: maintenance, deps, tooling — no behavior change
- refactor: code restructure with no behavior change
- test: adding or fixing tests
- docs: documentation only

## **Branch Strategy**

- Branches are named: type/ticket-short-description — e.g., feat/AUTH-142-google-login
- Branches live for hours to 2 days maximum, not weeks
- main branch is always deployable. Always.
- No direct pushes to main ever. PRs only, with required review and passing CI.

## **CI Pipeline — Required Gates (in order)**

| **#** | **Gate**             | **Target Time** | **Fails On**                         |
| ----- | -------------------- | --------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| 1     | Secret scanning      | < 30s           | Any credential pattern in code       |
| 2     | Linting + formatting | < 60s           | Any style violation                  |
| 3     | Unit tests           | < 3 min         | Any failure or < 70% coverage        |
| 4     | Integration tests    | < 5 min         | Any failure                          |
| 5     | Security scan (SAST) | < 2 min         | High/critical vulnerabilities        |
| 6     | Build artifact       | < 3 min         | Build failure                        |
| 7     | Deploy to staging    | < 5 min         | Health check failure → auto rollback |

**RULE:** Total CI time target: under 10 minutes. Pipelines that take 30+ minutes get bypassed. Fast feedback is the only kind that gets acted on.

## **Feature Flags**

Incomplete features are deployed behind a flag, not on a branch. A flag lets you merge to main continuously without releasing to users. Use LaunchDarkly, Unleash, or a simple DB-backed config table. The branch is never a substitute for a flag.

# **10. Dependency & Configuration Management**

## **Configuration Rules**

- Zero hardcoded values in source code. Every value that differs between environments lives in environment variables.
- Config is loaded once at startup into a typed config object. Never call os.getenv() or process.env.X inside business logic.
- Missing required env vars crash the app at startup with a clear error — not at runtime during a user request.

| **❌  BAD # Bad: scattered env calls in business logicclass PaymentService:    def charge(self, amount):        key = os.getenv("STRIPE_KEY")  # could be None!        url = "**[**https://hardcoded-stripe.com**](https://hardcoded-stripe.com)**"** | **✅  GOOD # Good: config loaded once, validated at startup# config.pyclass Config:    STRIPE_KEY: str = os.getenv("STRIPE_KEY")    STRIPE_URL: str = os.getenv("STRIPE_URL")        def validate(self):        if not self.STRIPE_KEY:            raise RuntimeError("STRIPE_KEY is required")#** [**payment.service.py**](http://payment.service.py)**  class PaymentService:    def __init__(self, config: Config):        self.stripe_key = config.STRIPE_KEY** |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |

## **Dependency Management**

- All dependency versions are pinned in a lock file (package-lock.json, Pipfile.lock, poetry.lock)
- Run automated dependency audits in CI (npm audit, pip-audit, Dependabot)
- Every new dependency requires: What does it solve? What is its maintenance status? What is its license? Could we write this in < 50 lines instead?
- Prefer small, focused packages over large frameworks for simple needs
- Shared internal libraries live in a private registry — never copy-pasted between repos

# **11. Security & Secrets**

*Any secret that has ever touched version control must be considered compromised and rotated immediately, regardless of whether you 'quickly deleted the commit'.*

## **Secrets Rules — Absolute**

- No secrets in code. No secrets in comments. No secrets in git history.
- Use a secrets manager: AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, or Doppler.
- Run secret-scanning on every commit (gitleaks, truffleHog) as a CI gate — step 1, before anything else.
- Rotate any credential that was ever committed, even briefly.

## **Input Validation — Where and How**

- Validate all input at the entry point (controller layer) before it reaches the service layer
- Use a schema validation library — don't write manual if/else chains for validation
- Never trust user input for SQL queries. Use parameterized queries always.
- Never use eval(), exec(), or dynamic code execution with user input

## **Principle of Least Privilege**

- Service accounts have only the DB permissions they need: an API service does not need DROP TABLE
- Internal microservices authenticate each other — no service blindly trusts another
- Tokens and sessions expire. Always. Default to short expiry with refresh.

# **12. Team & Ownership Practices**

## **CODEOWNERS File**

Every module/feature has a declared owning team. PRs touching that module automatically require review from that team. This is enforced via a CODEOWNERS file, not by memory.

\# .github/CODEOWNERS/src/users/         @team-identity/src/orders/        @team-commerce/src/payments/      @team-payments @team-security/infra/             @team-platform/shared/            @team-platform

## **Code Review Checklist**

Reviewers check this list — not just 'does the code look right'. Linters handle style. Reviewers handle these:

- Does this add duplication? Is there existing shared code that should be used?
- Is every try block handled? Are exceptions meaningful and domain-specific?
- Are logs structured with context? Are any secrets logged?
- Is the main file still clean? Has any logic leaked into it?
- Are new files in the correct feature folder?
- Are tests present for every new function and every edge case?
- Does any function exceed 40 lines? Any file exceed 400 lines?
- Is configuration hardcoded anywhere?

## **The Boy Scout Rule**

Leave every file you touch slightly better than you found it. Fix one bad variable name. Remove one commented-out block. Add one missing test. Over thousands of PRs, this compounds into a dramatically cleaner codebase — without a big-bang rewrite that will never be approved.

**RULE:** Big-bang rewrites almost never ship. Incremental improvement always does.

# **13. Performance & Observability**

## **Observability — The Three Pillars**

| **Pillar**          | **Tool Examples**               | **What It Tells You**                  |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Structured Logs     | ELK, Datadog, CloudWatch        | What happened and in what context      |
| Metrics             | Prometheus, Datadog, CloudWatch | How the system is performing over time |
| Distributed Tracing | Jaeger, Zipkin, OpenTelemetry   | Where time is spent across services    |

## **Performance Budgets — Enforced in CI**

- API response time P95 < 500ms. Alert at > 300ms.
- DB queries > 100ms must be logged and investigated. > 500ms is a bug.
- Frontend bundle size: set a budget per-bundle and fail CI if exceeded
- Memory usage: services should not grow unbounded over time (monitor for leaks)

## **What to Always Instrument**

- Every external HTTP call: duration, status code, endpoint
- Every DB query: duration, table, query type (read/write)
- Every queue message: enqueue time, processing time, failure count
- Every cache operation: hit/miss ratio
- Business metrics: orders per minute, signups per hour, payment success rate

## **Local Development**

Every engineer should be able to run the full stack locally in under 5 minutes using a single command. Use Docker Compose for all service dependencies. Provide seed data scripts. Document this in the repo root README — not in a Confluence page that is 3 years out of date.

\# Every repo must have thisdocker-compose up          # Start all dependenciesmake seed                  # Load development datamake dev                   # Start the servicemake test                  # Run full test suite

**The Governing Principle**

*A mediocre convention applied uniformly across an entire team beats a perfect convention applied sporadically by the best engineer. At scale, predictability and consistency are the most valuable features a codebase can have.*

**Write code for the engineer who comes after you — at 2am, during an incident, under pressure.**
